      "hovered_text": "AI Overview\nLeaves change color in autumn because shorter days and cooler temperatures signal trees to stop producing chlorophyll\u2014the pigment that drives photosynthesis and gives leaves their green color. As chlorophyll breaks down, previously masked yellow, orange, and red pigments are revealed.\u00a0\nSUNY ESF\n\u00a0+1\nThe vibrant fall foliage is driven by three main pigments that dictate the exact colors you see:\nChlorophyll (Green): Abundant during spring and summer, it absorbs sunlight to convert into energy. It masks all other pigments until the tree begins to prepare for winter.\nCarotenoids (Yellow & Orange): These pigments are always present in the leaf but are hidden by the overwhelming green of chlorophyll. When chlorophyll fades, yellow and orange colors shine through. They are the same pigments found in carrots and corn.\nAnthocyanins (Red & Purple): Unlike carotenoids, these are actively produced in autumn. They are created when sugars get trapped in the leaf as it prepares to drop.\u00a0\nSmithsonian Institution\n\u00a0+6\nMostra altro"
